  "reasoning": "The article reports kinetic assays (Michaelis‑Menten) for the peroxidase‑like activity of Fe₃O₄ nanoparticles and several molecularly‑imprinted nanogels (NIP, T‑MIP, T‑MIP⁻, A‑MIP, A‑MIP⁺).  \nFor each catalyst the authors give Vmax (µM min⁻¹) and Km (µM) for oxidation of two substrates, TMB and ABTS, in the presence of a fixed H₂O₂ concentration (10 mM).  \nThese data satisfy the requirement “kinetic assay was performed”.  \n\nAll experiments share the same physical characteristics of the Fe₃O₄ core:\n- Formula: Fe₃O₄  \n- Crystal system: cubic (spinel)  \n- Particle size ≈ 30 nm (TEM)  \n- Catalyst concentration in the assay: 50 µg mL⁻¹ (≈ 1.1 nM)  \n- Buffer: acetate, pH 4.0  \n- Temperature: 25 °C  \n- Reaction type: substrate + H₂O₂ (TMB+H₂O₂ or ABTS+H₂O₂)  \n\nFor each catalyst‑substrate pair a separate experiment object is created, containing:\n- Vmax (numeric mantissa) and unit “µM min⁻¹”  \n- Km converted to mM (µM ÷ 1000) with unit “mM”  \n- Fixed co‑substrate concentration (H₂O₂) = 10 mM (c_const)  \n- Substrate concentration range (c_min = 0.025 mM, c_max = 0.30 mM)  \n- Catalyst concentration (ccat_value = 50, ccat_unit = “µg mL⁻¹”)  \n\nThe extracted experiments are listed below in the order they appear in the paper."
